Lynn, Norfolk, England":"King's Lynn, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1435–1487":"1435–1487","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1437–1491":"1437–1491","1456–Female":"1456–Deceased","1459–Male":"1459–Deceased","1460–Male":"1460–Deceased","1461–Male":"1461–Deceased","1463–Female":"1463–Deceased","1465–Female":"1465–Deceased","1468–Male":"1468–Deceased","1469–1518":"1469–1518","1415–1445":"1415–1445","1415–Female":"1415–Deceased","1461":"1461","1460":"1460","1491":"1491","1459":"1459","1415":"1415","1437":"1437","1469":"1469","1435":"1435","1468":"1468","1445":"1445","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1465":"1465","1487":"1487","1463":"1463","1518":"1518","England":"England","Bishop's Lynn, Norfolk, England":"King's Lynn, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kinne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from the female personal name <i>Kinne</i>, a Silesian pet form of Middle High German <i>Kunigunde</i>, composed of the Old High German elements <i>kuoni</i> ‘brave’ + <i>gund</i> ‘battle’.","Flemish: variant of   Kin   2 and 3."],"variants":[{"name":"Kin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Sang, Young, Chong, Chun, Hak, Kwang, Song, Tae Wan, Yong, Yung, Aeja, Chin, Chul, Dong Joo, Dongil, Doo, Eng, Hee Chul, Hyeok, Hyung Joon, In-Young, Jong Woo, Min, Moon.","Polish: unexplained.","Dutch and Flemish: nickname for someone with a pointed or jutting chin, from Middle Dutch <i>kinne</i> ‘chin’."]}]},{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Kene","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Imre, Istvan, Janos, Sandor, Tibor.","Hungarian and Slovak: from a short form of the personal name Hungarian <i>Benedek</i>, Slovak <i>Benedikt</i> (see   Benedict  ).","Italian: from the personal name <i>Bene</i>, an omen or well-wishing name meaning ‘well, good’, or a short form of various compound omen or well-wishing names beginning with this element, such as <i>Benvenuto</i> ‘welcome’ and <i>Benenato</i> ‘well born’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beni","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Henri.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Bene  .","French: from <i>beni</i> ‘blessed’, the past participle of <i>bénir</i> ‘to bless’ (from Latin <i>benedicere</i>), presumably applied as a nickname, possibly with Christian overtones."]},{"name":"Benassi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Geno, Carlo, Carmello, Dante, Marco, Paolo, Primo.","Italian: probably a variant of <b>Benazzi</b>, a derivative of the personal name   Bene  ."]},{"name":"Benedict","meanings":["English, German, and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Benedict</i>, from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This owed its popularity in the Middle Ages chiefly to Saint Benedict of Norcia (<i>c.</i> 480–550), who founded the Benedictine order of monks at Monte Cassino and wrote a monastic rule that formed a model for all subsequent rules. No doubt the meaning of the Latin word also contributed to its popularity as a personal name, especially in Romance countries. Occasionally the English surname may derive from Latin <i>benedicite</i> ‘bless (you)’, perhaps given as a nickname to an habitual user of the expression. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed the German variant <b>Benedikt</b> and many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian   Benedek  , Slovenian <b>Benedik</b> (see   Benedick  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Italian   Benedetti  ."]},{"name":"Benanti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Sal, Antonio, Carmelo, Salvatore.","Italian: from a derivative of the personal name   Bene  ."]}]},{"name":"Roland","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In Old French literature it is borne by a legendary Frankish hero, a vassal of Charlemagne, whose exploits are told in the <i>Chanson de Roland</i>. The subject of the poem is Roland's death at the Battle of Roncesvalles in the Pyrenees in  778 , while protecting the rearguard of the Frankish army on its retreat from Spain. Roland is depicted in literature and legend as headstrong and impulsive. His devoted friendship with the prudent  Oliver  is also legendary."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowland","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roland  , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":20,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Roland Kinne De Kene was born in 1435, in England, his father, Curtis Kinne  De Kene, was 21 and his mother, Anna, was 21. He married Sarah Clarke in 1454. They were the parents of at least 5 sons and 3 daughters. He died in 1487, in his hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1435–1487":"1435–1487","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1437–1491":"1437–1491","1456–Female":"1456–Surnud","1459–Male":"1459–Surnud","1460–Male":"1460–Surnud","1461–Male":"1461–Surnud","1463–Female":"1463–Surnud","1465–Female":"1465–Surnud","1468–Male":"1468–Surnud","1469–1518":"1469–1518","1415–1445":"1415–1445","1415–Female":"1415–Surnud","1461":"1461","1460":"1460","1491":"1491","1459":"1459","1415":"1415","1437":"1437","1469":"1469","1435":"1435","1468":"1468","1445":"1445","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1465":"1465","1487":"1487","1463":"1463","1518":"1518","England":"England","Bishop's Lynn, Norfolk, England":"King's Lynn, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1435–1487":"1435–1487","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1437–1491":"1437–1491","1456–Female":"1456–Kuollut","1459–Male":"1459–Kuollut","1460–Male":"1460–Kuollut","1461–Male":"1461–Kuollut","1463–Female":"1463–Kuollut","1465–Female":"1465–Kuollut","1468–Male":"1468–Kuollut","1469–1518":"1469–1518","1415–1445":"1415–1445","1415–Female":"1415–Kuollut","1461":"1461","1460":"1460","1491":"1491","1459":"1459","1415":"1415","1437":"1437","1469":"1469","1435":"1435","1468":"1468","1445":"1445","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1465":"1465","1487":"1487","1463":"1463","1518":"1518","England":"England","Bishop's Lynn, Norfolk, England":"King's Lynn, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"1435–1487":"1435–1487","–Female":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1437–1491":"1437–1491","1456–Female":"1456–Décédée","1459–Male":"1459–Décédé","1460–Male":"1460–Décédé","1461–Male":"1461–Décédé","1463–Female":"1463–Décédée","1465–Female":"1465–Décédée","1468–Male":"1468–Décédé","1469–1518":"1469–1518","1415–1445":"1415–1445","1415–Female":"1415–Décédée","1461":"